%I A396884 #5 Jun 13 2026 17:51:58
%S A396884 1,1,1,1,4,5,39,13,26
%N A396884 Number of distinct smallest connected polyiamonds that contain every free n-iamond, up to rotations, reflections and translations of the triangular lattice.
%C A396884 A polyiamond is an edge-connected set of unit triangles drawn from the regular triangular tiling of the plane (vertex configuration 3.3.3.3.3.3, symmetry group p6m), whose cells alternate between upward- and downward-pointing triangles. A free n-iamond is one of the A000577(n) shapes of n such triangles, counted up to rotation and reflection.
%C A396884 A container for size n is a connected polyiamond that holds a copy of every free n-iamond as a sub-shape under the lattice symmetries; a(n) counts the containers of the smallest such size, themselves counted up to rotation, reflection and translation. That smallest size is A392363(n).
%C A396884 The sequence is non-monotonic: a(7) = 39, a(8) = 13, a(9) = 26. The square-lattice analog A352029 swings the same way, peaking at 204 then dropping to 7, so a jump in the minimum size A392363(n) can sharply cut the number of distinct minimal containers.
%C A396884 No closed form or low-order recurrence is known for the nine listed terms (conjectured to have none, UNVERIFIED). The listed values are the number of minimum-size containers found within a finite search window whose width equals n (forced by the straight n-iamond) and whose height grows as max(4, floor((n+2)/3)); global minimality over all bounding boxes is conjectured but not separately certified.
%H A396884 Peter Exley, <a href="https://github.com/pexley-math/oeis-A396884">Paper and figures</a>, GitHub.
%Y A396884 Cf. A000577 (free n-iamonds, the shapes to be contained), A001420 (fixed n-iamonds), A352029 (square-lattice analog, minimalist polyomino containers), A392363 (minimum container size for size n).
